Id enim jus si ad omnes spectat res subditorum, quidni etiam ad jus ex promisso bellico na- tum? quod si conceditur, videntur inanes fore omnes tales pactioneS‚ ac proinde belli nisi per victoriam finiendi spes nulla. Sed notandum contra est, jus illud supereminens non promiscue competere, sed quatenus communiter expedit in regimine non dominico sed civili, etiam regio. Plerumque autem communiter expedit pacta talia servari, quo ea perti- nent quae de praesenti statu tuendo alibi dicta a nobis sunt. Adde quod ubi hujus dominii usum res exigit, compensatio tamen facienda est, ut infra latius explicabitur.

VIII. 1 Praeterea possunt pacta sanciri jurejurando, nec tantum a rege aut senatu, sed et ab ipsa civitate, quo- modo in leges suas Lacedaemonios jurare fecit Lycurgus, Athe- nienses Solon, et ne personarum mutatione jus jurisjurandi intercideret, repeti quotannis jusjurandum4. Id enim si fiat, omnino ne publicae quidem utilitatis causa recedendum a pro- misso erit: nam et de suo cedere civitas potuit, et verba pos- sunt ita esse aperta ut nullam exceptionem admittant. eminent dominion over the goods of the subjects3 which rights are exercised in its name by the supreme authority. For if that right extend to all the possessions of the subjeets, why should it not extend to the right arising from a promise made in war? And if this be granted, it would seem that all conventions must be of no force, and consequently, that there is no way of terminating a war but by vic- tory. But on the other side, it is to be noted, that that eminent right does not extend to evei-ything promiscuously, but so far as it is expe- dient, as a part, not of a master’s authority, but of civil or royal autho- rity. And in general, it is expedient that such conventions should be observed; to which point pertains what we have elsewhere said, of maintaining the present state of things. Add to this, that when the case requires the exereise of this eminent dominion, compensation is to be made, as will be explained more at length below.
